               <head>Tabaqat-i Nasiri</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Ṭabaqāt-i Nāṣirī by Minhāj Sirāj Jūzjānī </summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/n2015015056 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh2008104967 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85064938" n="1" xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_3745-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied" key="person_237135946">Minhāj Sirāj Jūzjānī  </persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="per" type="supplied" key="person_237135946">م‍ن‍ه‍اج‌ س‍راج‌ جوزجانی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_6201">Ṭabaqāt-i Nāṣirī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_6201">طبقات ناصری</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>General history with special reference to the Muslim ruling dynasties of India, written over the years <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari">657-8</date>/<date calendar="#Gregorian">1259-60</date>
                        </p>
                        <p>The author was born at Fīrūzkūh (Khurāsān) in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari">589</date>/<date calendar="#Gregorian">1193</date>, and travelled to India in <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari">624</date>, where he became a high offcial of Nāṣir al-Dīn Maḥmūd ibn Altmish (or Iltutmish) to whom this work is dedicated
                        </p>
                        <p>Orthography and diacritics unusual</p>
                        <p>Naskh script by Yaʿqūb ibn Ibrāhīm Ghūrī (?). Illuminated and coloured rulings. Damaged. Poorly repaired </p>
                        <p>Pencil annotations by H G Raverty</p>
                        <p>Defective at end</p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>
						</note>
                  </msItem>
